rsonal`, `shared`, custom) keeps working unchanged.\n\n## Non-goals\n\n- Changing how the `private` tier behaves. It never leaves the machine, unchanged.\n- Encryption of hub content (the `shared`-tier encryption ADR is separate).\n- Per-team namespace keys. The model leaves room for them but we do not build them.\n\n## Core model: one sync path, a per-binding namespace\n\nSync stays a single code path. kref delegates all transport to git-bug's dag package,\nwhich names refs from one namespace string (`entry.Definition(t).Namespace`) and pushes\nthem with a symmetric refspec `refs/\u003cns\u003e/*:refs/\u003cns\u003e/*` (`repository.PushRefs`,\ngogit.go). There is no local-differs-from-remote mapping, and `GoGitRepo` exposes no raw\ngo-git handle to build one. So the namespace we sync under is the namespace we store\nunder, both ends.\n\nThe scoping therefore lives in the namespace, resolved per binding:\n\n| Binding mode | Namespace                | Registry consulted | Refs (local and wire)          |\n|--------------|--------------------------|--------------------|--------------------------------|\n| flat         | `kref-\u003ctier\u003e`            | never              | `refs/kref-\u003ctier\u003e/*`, today    |\n| hub          | `kref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cspace-id\u003e` | yes (bootstrap)    | `refs/kref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cspace-id\u003e/*`|\n\nThe space-id is a slash-free suffix, not a path segment. It must be slash-free because\ngit-bug's `AllClocks` enumerates lamport clocks with a non-recursive `os.ReadDir` of the\n`clocks/` directory (gogit.go); a `/` in the namespace would nest the clock file and\nbreak clock loading (silent sync corruption). A suffix keeps the clock name flat.\n\nOne hub repo therefore holds sibling namespaces `refs/kref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cidA\u003e/*`,\n`refs/kref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cidB\u003e/*`, one per space, and aggregates them all. Scoping is native\ngit behaviour, not a client-side prune: a hub pull is `FetchRefs(remote,\nkref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cyourid\u003e)`, so git negotiates and packs objects only for your namespace.\nOther spaces' content never crosses the wire (see Reads for the two metadata caveats).\n\n\"Flat vs hub\" is which namespace the binding resolves, not a branch in the transport. A\n`namespaceFor(tier)` seam replaces the bare `t.Namespace()` in the store's read, write,\npush, pull, and pushed-state paths. A non-hubbed tier resolves to `kref-\u003ctier\u003e` exactly\nas today, so flat behaviour (including team `shared`) is unchanged and needs no\nmigration.\n\nThe `--hub` flag on the remote binding selects the hub namespace. The default follows\ntier type: personal-typed bindings default to hub (safe: your own repos either run solo,\nwhere scoping is invisible, or many, where scoping is what you want), and collaborative\n`shared` bindings default to flat (converging with teammates is the point of a team\ntier, and scoping would silently un-share you).\n\nInvariant: a given (tier + target) is uniformly flat or uniformly hub. The two produce\ndifferent namespaces (`kref-\u003ctier\u003e` vs `kref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cid\u003e`), so a single tier is stored\nunder exactly one of them at a time; switching modes is a migration (see Changing\nremotes), never a mix.\n\nCost this imposes, budgeted in the plan: because the local namespace changes when a tier\nis hubbed, `kref hub set` performs a one-time, lossless re-home of existing\n`refs/kref-\u003ctier\u003e/*` entries into `refs/kref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cspace-id\u003e/*` (copy, witness clocks,\nverify, then remove the old refs). Entity ids are namespace-independent, so identity and\nlinks are preserved.\n\n## Space identity and lifecycle\n\nA \"space\" is one repo's slice on a hub. Its id is:\n\n- Opaque and random, minted at `kref init`. It is not derived from the repo name, so\n  renaming or moving the repo never changes the space.\n- Immutable in normal use. There is no casual rename.\n- Backfilled: an existing store with no id mints one on first hub-relevant use.\n\nStorage: the local id is machine-local bookkeeping in a ref that never syncs, following\nthe existing `refs/kref-pushed/*` precedent. It carries the id and the normalized origin\nit bound to. Nothing enters the working tree. If the local record is lost it is\nrecoverable from the registry (below).\n\nRebind is the one deliberate escape hatch, for the two cases pure immutability would\nhurt:\n\n- `kref hub rebind --adopt \u003cid\u003e`: reattach to an existing space after local config loss.\n- `kref hub rebind --fresh`: give a forked clone its own id so it stops colliding with\n  the repo it was forked from.\n\nBoth writes are loud and update the local record and the registry.\n\n## Bootstrap and registry (cross-machine convergence)\n\nkref refs do not travel with `git clone` (a normal clone fetches `refs/heads/*` and\n`refs/tags/*` only). So a fresh clone on a second machine has no local id and no entries\nuntil it pulls. To learn which space is \"this repo's\" before it knows its id, a cold\nclone consults a flat, non-space-scoped registry on the hub.\n\nRegistry:\n\n- Namespace `refs/kref-registry/*` on the hub. Not space-scoped, since it is read before\n  a space-id is known.\n- Entries are hidden kref entries mapping a hashed origin to a space-id.\n- The origin URL is normalized (strip `.git`, canonicalize scheme) and, critically, has\n  any userinfo/credentials stripped before hashing. An origin can carry a token\n  (`https://user:TOKEN@host/...`); it must never reach storage. We strip proactively at\n  the boundary; the push scan is a backstop, not the primary control.\n- The stored key is a salted hash of the normalized origin, not the plaintext URL. The\n  hub therefore does not hold a readable inventory of the user's repositories. The cost\n  is that `--all` labels a space by its id rather than a human-readable origin.\n- The salt is per-hub, stored once in the registry namespace, so any machine that pulls\n  the registry reproduces the same hash. This is decided (see Decisions). An independent\n  per-machine salt is not viable: two machines would hash the same origin differently,\n  the lookup would always miss, and convergence (the reason the registry exists) would\n  break. A shared user-secret salt kept off the hub would hide origins even from a hub\n  reader, but at the cost of per-machine setup and manual recovery on secret loss; it is\n  the documented upgrade path for a less-trusted hub, not the default.\n\nCold-clone flow (hub configured once per machine via `kref hub set \u003curl\u003e`):\n\n1. No local id (entries did not clone).\n2. Normalize `origin`, strip credentials, hash with the salt.\n3. Pull the registry; look up the hash.\n4. Hit: adopt that space-id, then `sync pull` this space. Converged, no prompts.\n5. Miss: mint a fresh id, register `hash -\u003e id`, push. This is machine one for the repo.\n\nConcurrent first-init on two machines is rare but handled: both mint, both claim the\nsame origin hash. A deterministic winner (earliest, or lexically smallest id) is\ncanonical; the loser detects \"my id differs from the registry canonical for my origin\"\nand auto-rebinds, loudly. Nothing is silent, nothing is lost.\n\nRepos with no `origin` still work on one machine (mint a local id) but cannot\nauto-converge elsewhere, since there is nothing to hash. This is warned, not errored\n(see guardrails).\n\n## Reads: default scope and `--all`\n\n- Default `list`, `search`, `show`, and `sync pull` operate on this repo's namespace\n  (`kref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cspace-id\u003e`) only. Scoping is native: `FetchRefs` transfers objects for\n  the matching namespace alone.\n- `--all` on read commands and `sync pull` spans every space on the hub. Other spaces are\n  fetched into separate, read-only local namespaces surfaced only under `--all` and\n  tagged by origin space. Read-only is deliberate: an agent trawling the whole corpus\n  must not be able to mutate another repo's entry from the wrong context.\n- The registry is the enumeration source for `--all` (it lists every space on the hub).\n\nTwo metadata caveats, neither about entry content:\n\n- Ref-name advertisement. Depending on whether go-git negotiates with git protocol v2\n  ref-prefix filtering, a scoped fetch may still receive the server's full ref-name\n  advertisement (every space's namespace). That exposes opaque ids, not content, and on a\n  private personal hub it is the user's own data. Noted, not blocking.\n- Identity refs are not space-scoped, so `identity.Pull` brings down all authors on the\n  hub. Trivial for a personal hub (the user plus any agent actors); relevant only if a\n  hub were ever multi-person.\n\n## Secret boundary and degradation (unchanged)\n\n- A hub is an ordinary git remote of the tier's type, so `kref sync push` still scans the\n  delta about to leave and fails closed on a hit. No new bypass.\n- No hub configured means no `--hub` binding, which means today's behaviour verbatim.\n  The feature is a superset, opt-in via one command, degrading to nothing.\n\n## Changing remotes: reset semantics\n\nPushed-state is keyed by namespace, not remote: `pushedRef` is\n`refs/kref-pushed/\u003cnamespace\u003e/\u003cid\u003e` (`pushed.go`), and `pushDelta` skips any entry whose\ntip matches its pushed mirror. So kref's \"already pushed\" has no notion of which remote\nsaw the content. Pointing a binding at a new hub without clearing pushed-state makes\n`pushDelta` return empty, and the new hub silently receives nothing. This is the footgun\nthe design must close.\n\nChanging a remote is a targeted reset of derived state, never a content purge. Git\nobjects are content-addressed and canonical refs are removed only after a verified copy,\nso the real KB is never lost and a crash mid-operation is idempotent to re-run (both\nnamespaces present, never neither).\n\nCase 1, the namespace changes (`hub set` flat-\u003ehub, `hub rebind --adopt|--fresh`,\nun-hub):\n\n1. Copy canonical refs `refs/kref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cold\u003e/*` -\u003e the new namespace, witnessing clocks\n   under it.\n2. Remove old canonical refs.\n3. Remove old pushed mirrors `refs/kref-pushed/kref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cold\u003e/*`.\n4. Remove old remote-tracking refs `refs/remotes/\u003coldremote\u003e/kref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cold\u003e/*`.\n5. Clear the tier's incoming marker.\n6. The new namespace has no pushed mirrors, so the next push is a full, freshly scanned\n   re-push. Correct by construction; the pushed-state reset is automatic here.\n\nCase 2, the remote changes but the namespace stays (repoint the same space at a\ndifferent or fresh hub URL): content does not move, but pushed-state is now stale, so:\n\n1. Clear pushed mirrors for the namespace, forcing a full re-scan and re-push.\n2. Refresh or drop the old remote-tracking refs.\n3. Clear the incoming marker.\n4. Drop the read-only `--all` cache, which is stale relative to the new hub and is safe\n   to re-fetch.\n\nGuarantees the reset upholds: no content loss (copy, verify, then remove); the secret\nboundary is re-armed for the new destination (a full re-push re-scans the whole history\nbefore it leaves); and it is loud (every remote change reports \"re-pushing N entries to\n\u003cremote\u003e\", so an un-synced backlog is never mistaken for a completed backup).\n\n## Intuitiveness guardrails\n\nThe machinery is invisible: the user touches `kref hub set \u003curl\u003e` once per machine, then\nnormal commands, plus `--all`. The failure mode of hidden machinery is silent surprise,\nso the rule is: never expose the internals; when an edge fires, print one honest line and\nthe single command that fixes it.\n\nFour edges and their narration:\n\n1. Cold clone looks empty. First run reports \"hub configured; N entries in this space,\n   run `kref sync pull`\" (or auto-pulls on adopt).\n2. \"Where did my entry go?\" A repo-scoped default surprises without the model. `show` and\n   `list` headers name the space so it is never a mystery.\n3. No `origin`. Warn at `hub set` / first push: this space will not auto-converge on\n   other machines; set an origin or use `hub rebind --adopt`.\n4. Origin URL changes (repo moves host). The hash changes, so a cold clone would mint a\n   new space and old history appears to vanish under the old hash. Detect \"origin changed\n   since bind\", warn, and let `hub rebind --adopt \u003cid\u003e` re-anchor.\n\nTerminology: keep the word \"space\" out of the common path. Day to day this is \"your\npersonal notes, per repo.\" \"Space\" appears only in `hub` subcommands and `--all` labels.\n\n## Command surface\n\n- `kref hub set \u003curl\u003e`: sugar for `kref remote set personal hub \u003curl\u003e --hub`. The 95%\n  path stays one intuitive line.\n- `kref remote set \u003ctier\u003e \u003cname\u003e \u003curl\u003e --hub`: general form. Any tier can be hubbed; the\n  flag selects the hub resolver. Omitting `--hub` is the flat binding.\n- `kref hub rebind --adopt \u003cid\u003e | --fresh`: the escape hatch.\n- `--all`: on `list`, `search`, and `sync pull`.\n\n## Backward compatibility\n\nNone required for flat bindings: `namespaceFor` resolves a non-hubbed tier to\n`kref-\u003ctier\u003e`, reproducing today's ref layout exactly. Existing `personal`, `shared`, and\ncustom remotes keep syncing without change. Hub is new behaviour reached only by a new\nflag, and it changes a tier's local namespace only for that tier, only once hubbed, via\nthe `hub set` migration.\n\n## Phased build\n\nPhase 1 (prove the idea end to end):\n\n- The `namespaceFor(tier)` seam threaded through the store's read, write, push, pull, and\n  pushed-state paths, resolving `kref-\u003ctier\u003e` (flat) or `kref-\u003ctier\u003e-\u003cspace-id\u003e` (hub).\n- Flat resolution expressing existing behaviour through the seam, verified byte-identical\n  to today.\n- Space-id: local-only ref storage, mint at init, backfill.\n- Hashed-origin registry: normalize and credential-strip origin, per-hub salt, cold-clone\n  adopt/mint, concurrent-init deterministic winner.\n- `hub set`: bind the remote and run the lossless flat-\u003ehub re-home migration.\n- Changing-remotes reset (both cases), loud re-push.\n- Personal hub working across two machines.\n- `--all` read-only view.\n- Guardrail warnings for the four edges (they are the safety net, not polish).\n\nPhase 2 (round off intuitiveness):\n\n- Origin-alias handling (multiple origin hashes per space for host moves).\n- Auto-pull on adopt, richer space headers.\n- Concurrent-init resolution refinements.\n\nScoped `shared` and scoped custom tiers need no new code. They are the same hub resolver\npointed at a different tier, available the day someone sets `--hub` on that binding.\n\n## Decisions\n\n- Origin-hash salt is per-hub, stored once in the registry namespace. Rationale: it is\n  the only zero-setup option that preserves cross-machine convergence, and for a private\n  personal hub the privacy a per-machine user-secret would add is marginal, since a hub\n  reader who could recover the repo list already sees the entry content beside it. A\n  user-secret salt kept off the hub is the documented upgrade path for a less-trusted\n  hub; keeping salt resolution behind the `resolveKey` seam makes that a local change.\n\n## Open questions and risks\n\n- Registry contention at scale (many repos initialized in a burst). Expected low; the\n  deterministic-winner rule bounds the damage to one auto-rebind.\n- Whether `hub set` should offer to `sync pull` immediately on first adopt, or leave it\n  explicit. Leaning offer-then-confirm."},{"type":3,"timestamp":1783190700,"nonce":"HsphaPuqGr3r0mt58YrwGo5EDO8=","body":"# Hub sync (spaces): scoped-per-repo tier aggregation into one remote\n\nDesign spec, draft for review. Status: proposed. Author intent captured 2026-07-04.\n\n## Problem\n\nA person works across many local repositories. Personal knowledg